sentence: Stocks were higher in mid-day trade, with the Nasdaq Composite index in recent minutes pushing past its record high close set in March 2000 as Wall Street was working to overcome lackluster earnings and disappointing housing and manufacturing data.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average Thursday also pushed through yesterday's 18050 high while the S&P 500 was also posting constructive gains.
The Nasdaq Composite index was up more than 19 points, or 0.4%, to 5054.75 in recent intraday trading, topping its all-time closing high of 5048.62 set during the dot-com bubble on March 10, 2000.
The Nasdaq was still well under its all-time intraday high of 5132.52, also set on March 10, 2000.

Equities began U.S. trade underwater in sympathy with European markets after manufacturing data from Asia and the EU all missed expectations, with the Japanese and Chinese purchasing managers index contracting further from month ago levels.

The pressure on U.S. equities mounted after General Motors ( GM ), Proctor and Gamble ( PG ) and Union Pacific ( UNP ) all reported disappointing Q1 financial results, overshadowing an earnings beat from Caterpillar ( CAT ) and EBAY ( EBAY ), as well as better-than-expected earnings from Facebook (FB).
Today's economic data was also a catalyst for early selling.
Initial jobless claims rose 1,000 to 295,000 last week, reversing consensus estimates looking for a 8,000 decline to 286,000 claims.
Rounding out the sluggish global manufacturing data was a miss in the U.S. PMI, dropping to a 54.2 reading for April from 55.7 in March, missing estimates for a small gain to 56.0.
The Kansas City Fed reported a similar drop in factory activity in the American midwest, with its manufacturing index falling to a negative 7 reading from a negative 4 score the prior month.
Also today, new home sales fell by over 11% in March to a seasonally-adjusted annual rate of 481,000, well below estimates for a 3.9% decline to 518,000.
European equities ended mostly lower today after EU-zone production data missed estimates.
France's PMI slipped further into contraction mode while Germany fell to 51.9 from 52.8 in March, causing the EU-zone index to weaken to 51.9 from 52.2 the month prior.
Crude oil was up $1.75 to $57.91 per barrel.
Natural gas was down $0.08 to $2.58 per 1 million BTU.
Gold was up $3.80 to $1,190.50 an ounce, while silver was up $0.01 to $15.81 an ounce.
Copper was up $0.02 to $2.70 per pound.
Among energy ETFs, the United States Oil Fund was up 2.84% to $19.91 with the United States Natural Gas Fund was down 2.49% to $12.72.
Amongst precious-metal funds, the Market Vectors Gold Miners ETF was down 0.68% to 21.56 while SPDR Gold Shares were up 0.44% to $114.33.
The iShares Silver Trust was up 0.27% to $15.15.
